    {
      "id": "ff5088acd474baa7341b3f3b7322c1eb0caf9cf0",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2018-10-20 18:45:38.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Verified-1\n\nFailed enforced test review-ldiskfs on CentOS 7.0/x86_64 uploaded by Onyx Autotest from onyx-43vm1: https://testing.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/45dbed71-7f87-4e09-a25a-6b6a28f8f58f ran 4 tests.  1 tests failed: sanity.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "2a820dcc68b044ba557a6a6c1d01bf4a6858d1bc",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 308,
        "name": "Amir Shehata",
        "email": "ashehata@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "ashehata"
      },
      "date": "2018-10-22 17:08:13.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nfpo_is_fmr is set to true here: kiblnd_alloc_fmr_pool()\nkiblnd_create_fmr_pool() calls kiblnd_alloc_fmr_pool()\nif kiblnd_alloc_fmr_pool() fails to allocate the fmr pool the fpo is freed in out_fpo in kiblnd_create_fmr_pool()\nSo how could fpo_is_fmr be true but fpo_fmr_pool be NULL?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "7aeb138ae399c4daafcdeed9cc5f2f19ad899972",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2018-10-22 17:59:53.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nCurrently that is the case but the way the code is written opens the possibility of this type of error. Can you guarentee this will always do the right thing. This new code makes it clear what the right thing is.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "fd2e1cc19329c42305ad1ec4b289b15876943912",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2018-10-22 18:24:54.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nDo you wish me just to reword the commit message then to point out this prevents any potential bugs.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "4af109f42553db45bafa596c58a9370c3368f8d3",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 308,
        "name": "Amir Shehata",
        "email": "ashehata@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "ashehata"
      },
      "date": "2018-10-22 18:46:29.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nI think the source of the confusion is that we set fpo_is_fmr to true even if we don't successfully allocate the fmr pool. If we clean that up, then it would be enough to check if (fmr_is_fmr) before destroying. We don't need to check the pool if it's NULL. I think that would make it clearer. We set a flag that we use to check if fmr is enable on that pool everywhere in the code. What do you think?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "c5606c4c8dccf51d11ce07c396fce126d8d6782f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 308,
        "name": "Amir Shehata",
        "email": "ashehata@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "ashehata"
      },
      "date": "2018-10-22 18:47:05.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n*fpo_is_fmr",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "d56ded0d00630323266539f3ffbcbc3110d44909",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 308,
        "name": "Amir Shehata",
        "email": "ashehata@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "ashehata"
      },
      "date": "2018-10-22 18:53:13.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nMy issue is that we make decisions based on two things that really mean the same thing. We should just stick with checking the fpo_is_fmr since that's only set when an fmr pool is allocated for that fpo.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "028e55f462930f4889b439a3d744ef988b733063",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2018-10-22 18:55:34.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nI see two conditions. One can be handled by the dev_caps which will tell us if FMR or FastReg is used. The second it to let us know if a pool for one of those features is enabled. Then is_fmr becomes bool pool_allocated.  That makes it more clear. is_fmr existed before we had the nice dev_caps that you implemented. Does that sound reasonable?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "f5747fe768d86635a78071db3a7ae45099e08d0f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 308,
        "name": "Amir Shehata",
        "email": "ashehata@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "ashehata"
      },
      "date": "2018-10-22 20:42:15.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nthe IBLND_DEV_CAPS_[FASTREG | FMR]_ENABLED is used at the device level. This tell us if the device supports FASTREG or FMR. the fpo_is_fmr is intended to tell us if the pool has allocated an FMR pool, so we can destroy it later. It's also used in kiblnd_fmr_pool_unmap/map(). It is feasible that a device can support FMR but we end up using fastreg as an example. \n\nSo if the proposal is to change the name to fmr_pool_allocated, I'm ok with that. Is that what you mean? or did you want to make some other changes?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "0c3e017e698b3662d5271a02c9d4d61e0d352bb3",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2018-10-23 03:46:23.000000000",
      "message": "Uploaded patch set 3.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "b4f56552c37ff653ee2bc7d7284436573b3e9c65",
